{
  "Which characteristic does NOT define a hazardous waste under EPA regulations?": "",
  "Biodegradability": "",
  "Ignitability": "",
  "Corrosivity": "",
  "Toxicity": "",
  "The EPA defines hazardous waste by four characteristics: ignitability, corrosivity, reactivity, and toxicity. Biodegradability is not a hazardous characteristic; in fact, biodegradable wastes are generally less concerning than persistent ones.": "",
  "What federal law governs the management of hazardous waste from generation to disposal in the United States?": "",
  "The Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA)": "",
  "The Clean Air Act": "",
  "The Endangered Species Act": "",
  "The National Environmental Policy Act": "",
  "RCRA, enacted in 1976, establishes the framework for managing hazardous waste from 'cradle to grave,' tracking waste from generation through transportation, treatment, storage, and final disposal.": "",
  "What is the primary purpose of a hazardous waste manifest?": "",
  "To list the ingredients in hazardous materials": "",
  "To advertise waste disposal services": "",
  "To track hazardous waste from its point of generation to its final disposal destination": "",
  "To calculate the cost of waste disposal": "",
  "A hazardous waste manifest is a shipping document that accompanies hazardous waste at every step of its journey, ensuring accountability and creating a paper trail from generator to transporter to treatment, storage, or disposal facility.": "",
  "Which of the following is considered a household hazardous waste?": "",
  "Newspaper": "",
  "Cardboard boxes": "",
  "Old paint, motor oil, and pesticides": "",
  "Glass bottles": "",
  "Household hazardous wastes include leftover paints, solvents, motor oil, batteries, pesticides, and cleaning chemicals. These should be disposed of at special collection events, not placed in regular trash or poured down drains.": "",
  "What is the primary danger of improper disposal of electronic waste (e-waste)?": "",
  "E-waste creates electromagnetic interference": "",
  "Toxic materials like lead, mercury, and cadmium can leach into soil and water": "",
  "E-waste takes up too much space in landfills": "",
  "E-waste attracts insects and rodents": "",
  "Electronic devices contain hazardous materials including lead in solder, mercury in switches and screens, cadmium in batteries, and brominated flame retardants. When improperly disposed of, these toxins leach into soil and groundwater.": "",
  "What method of hazardous waste disposal involves permanently sealing waste in underground rock formations?": "",
  "Deep well injection": "",
  "Incineration": "",
  "Open dumping": "",
  "Surface impoundment": "",
  "Deep well injection pumps liquid hazardous waste deep underground into porous rock formations that are sealed above and below by impermeable rock layers, isolating the waste from drinking water aquifers and the surface environment.": "",
  "What percentage of the world's e-waste is properly recycled according to global estimates?": "",
  "About 20%": "",
  "About 80%": "",
  "About 5%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "Only about 20% of global e-waste is formally recycled through proper channels. The remainder is landfilled, incinerated, or informally processed in developing countries under dangerous conditions, exposing workers to toxic materials.": "",
  "What is the Basel Convention?": "",
  "A nuclear weapons treaty": "",
  "A trade agreement for selling recycled materials": "",
  "A Swiss banking regulation": "",
  "An international treaty controlling the transboundary movement and disposal of hazardous waste": "",
  "The Basel Convention, adopted in 1989, aims to reduce the movement of hazardous waste between nations, specifically to prevent developed countries from dumping hazardous waste in developing countries with weaker environmental regulations.": "",
  "What is the most recycled material in the United States by weight?": "",
  "Aluminum, particularly regarding": "",
  "Steel and iron (from automobiles and appliances)": "",
  "Plastic, particularly regarding most": "",
  "Glass, particularly regarding losing": "",
  "Steel and iron are the most recycled materials by weight in the United States, with auto recycling being the largest recycling industry. Steel can be recycled indefinitely without losing quality.": "",
  "What is the approximate recycling rate for plastic in the United States?": "",
  "About 90%": "",
  "About 5-10%": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "Despite widespread collection programs, only about 5-10% of plastic waste in the United States is actually recycled. Many plastics are difficult to recycle due to the variety of resin types, contamination, and limited end markets.": "",
  "What is a 'cradle-to-grave' management system?": "",
  "A system for managing cemetery waste, particularly regarding manage when evaluated systematically": "",
  "A funeral home management approach, particularly regarding system when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "A regulatory system that tracks hazardous materials from creation through disposal, holding generators responsible at every stage": "",
  "A life insurance policy for waste management workers in most standard conditions": "",
  "Cradle-to-grave is a regulatory approach under RCRA that requires generators to track and manage hazardous waste from the point of creation (cradle) through transportation, treatment, storage, and final disposal (grave), ensuring accountability at every step.": "",
  "What does 'cradle-to-cradle' design mean?": "",
  "A method of manufacturing baby products": "",
  "A design philosophy where products are made to be fully recyclable or compostable, with materials continuously cycling through use": "",
  "Designing products to last from one generation to the next": "",
  "A type of rocking motion used in waste processing machinery": "",
  "Cradle-to-cradle design aims to eliminate waste by ensuring all materials in a product can either be safely returned to the biosphere (biological nutrients) or continuously recycled as industrial materials (technical nutrients), creating closed-loop systems.": "",
  "What is 'downcycling'?": "",
  "Reducing the price of recycled goods": "",
  "Recycling materials into products of lower quality or functionality than the original": "",
  "Moving waste downstream in a river system": "",
  "Cycling downhill on a bicycle made from recycled materials": "",
  "Downcycling occurs when recycled materials lose quality in the recycling process and can only be made into lower-grade products. For example, recycled plastic bottles are often downcycled into fiber for clothing or carpet rather than new bottles.": "",
  "What is a 'materials recovery facility' (MRF)?": "",
  "A plant that sorts, processes, and prepares recyclable materials for sale to manufacturers": "",
  "A hospital that recovers materials from surgical waste": "",
  "A facility that extracts raw materials from mines": "",
  "A warehouse for storing hazardous materials": "",
  "A MRF receives mixed recyclables collected from curbside programs, sorts them by material type using manual labor and automated equipment (magnets, optical scanners, air classifiers), and bales them for sale to manufacturers as feedstock.": "",
  "What does 'hazardous waste minimization' mean?": "",
  "Making hazardous waste less visible to inspectors": "",
  "Reducing the volume or toxicity of hazardous waste through process changes, substitution, or recycling": "",
  "Minimizing the cost of disposing hazardous waste": "",
  "Using the smallest containers possible for hazardous waste": "",
  "Hazardous waste minimization reduces either the volume or the toxicity of hazardous waste generated, through strategies like substituting less hazardous chemicals, modifying production processes, recycling solvents, and improving inventory management.": "",
  "What is 'contamination' in the context of recycling?": "",
  "Radioactive materials found in recycling bins": "",
  "The release of chemicals during the recycling process": "",
  "The spread of disease through recycled products": "",
  "Non-recyclable materials or food residue mixed with recyclables that reduces the quality or renders them unrecyclable": "",
  "Recycling contamination occurs when non-recyclable items (plastic bags, food-soiled containers, non-recyclable plastics) are placed in recycling bins, reducing the value of recyclables and sometimes causing entire loads to be sent to landfill.": "",
  "What does 'closed-loop recycling' mean?": "",
  "Recycling facilities that operate behind closed doors": "",
  "A loop of material that is too contaminated to recycle": "",
  "A system where a product is recycled back into the same type of product, maintaining material quality indefinitely": "",
  "A recycling program that has been permanently shut down": "",
  "Closed-loop recycling occurs when a material is recycled back into the same product without degradation. Aluminum cans are a prime example: they can be recycled back into new aluminum cans indefinitely with no loss of quality.": "",
  "What is 'life cycle assessment' (LCA)?": "",
  "A financial analysis of a company's profit over its lifetime": "",
  "An evaluation of a product's total environmental impact from raw material extraction through disposal or recycling": "",
  "An assessment of how long a product will last before breaking": "",
  "A medical assessment of a person's life expectancy": "",
  "LCA evaluates environmental impacts at every stage of a product's life: raw material extraction, manufacturing, transportation, use, and end-of-life disposal or recycling. It helps identify which stages have the greatest environmental footprint.": "",
  "What does 'RCRA Subtitle C' regulate?": "",
  "Air pollution from waste incineration": "",
  "Municipal solid waste recycling programs": "",
  "The management of hazardous waste, including generation, transportation, treatment, storage, and disposal": "",
  "Nuclear waste from power plants": "",
  "RCRA Subtitle C establishes the regulatory framework specifically for hazardous waste management, setting standards for generators, transporters, and treatment, storage, and disposal facilities (TSDFs) to ensure safe handling of hazardous materials.": "",
  "What is the meaning of 'waste characterization'?": "",
  "Categorizing waste by the character or personality of the person who generated it": "",
  "The process of analyzing waste to determine its composition, properties, and whether it is hazardous or non-hazardous": "",
