  "E-waste processing is always safe regardless of the methods used": "",
  "Despite the Basel Convention's restrictions on hazardous waste exports, large quantities of e-waste are shipped to developing countries labeled as 'used electronics' or 'donations.' Informal recycling exposes workers and communities to severe health hazards including lead poisoning and cancer.": "",
  "A chemical plant generates 1,000 tons of hazardous solvent waste per year. A process engineer proposes modifying the production process to use a water-based solvent instead, which would eliminate 80% of the hazardous waste while a closed-loop recovery system recycles the remaining 20%. What waste management hierarchy principle does this exemplify?": "",
  "Source reduction and recycling, the most preferred approaches in the waste management hierarchy": "",
  "Incineration, particularly regarding principle when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Deep well injection, particularly regarding this as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "Treatment and disposal, particularly regarding with when measured under": "",
  "This approach combines source reduction (switching to a less hazardous water-based solvent eliminates 80% of hazardous waste) with recycling (recovering and reusing the remaining solvent). These are the two most preferred strategies in the hazardous waste management hierarchy.": "",
  "A community discovers that a local auto repair shop has been illegally dumping used motor oil into a storm drain for 15 years. Testing shows petroleum contamination in the local creek and sediment. Under RCRA and the Clean Water Act, what enforcement actions can be taken?": "",
  "No action can be taken because the dumping occurred over a long period": "",
  "Only a verbal warning is permitted for first-time offenders": "",
  "The shop owner can face criminal penalties, civil fines, and be required to fund cleanup of the contaminated creek and sediment": "",
  "The community must pay for cleanup since they failed to report sooner": "",
  "Illegal disposal of hazardous waste (used motor oil is regulated under RCRA) and discharge of pollutants into waterways (Clean Water Act violation) can result in criminal prosecution, civil penalties up to tens of thousands of dollars per day of violation, and mandatory cleanup requirements.": "",
  "A hospital generates multiple types of waste: infectious biological waste from surgeries, pharmaceutical waste from expired medications, radioactive waste from diagnostic procedures, and regular office waste. Why does this make hospital waste management particularly complex?": "",
  "Hospitals produce less waste than typical businesses": "",
  "Hospital waste is not regulated by any environmental laws": "",
  "All hospital waste can be treated the same way": "",
  "Each waste type requires different handling, treatment, and disposal methods under different regulatory frameworks": "",
  "Hospitals generate a complex mix of waste streams each governed by different regulations: infectious waste requires autoclaving or incineration, pharmaceutical waste follows RCRA hazardous waste rules, radioactive waste follows NRC regulations, and each requires separate collection, training, and disposal pathways.": "",
  "A battery recycling facility processes 50,000 lithium-ion batteries per month from electric vehicles and consumer electronics. During processing, a fire breaks out because damaged batteries undergo thermal runaway. What does this incident highlight about the challenges of recycling modern batteries?": "",
  "Battery fires only occur in poorly managed facilities": "",
  "The fire was caused by non-battery materials in the facility": "",
